{
  "texts": [
    "LOO is also the oldest, dating back to Cook & Weisberg (1982) who term it case deletion diagnostics.",
    "As its name indicates, leave-one-out influence is the change in z te 's risk due to the removal of a single instance, z i, from the training set (Koh & Liang, 2017; Black & Fredrikson, 2021; Jia et al., 2021).",
    "Formally, where (T) D ⧵z i are the final model parameters when training on subset D⧵z i and (T) are the final model parameters trained on all of D.",
    "Measuring the entire training set's LOO influence requires training (n + 1) models.",
    "Given a deterministic model class and training algorithm [e.g., convex model optimization (Boyd & Vandenberghe, 2004) ], LOO is one of the few influence measures that can be computed exactly in polynomial time w.r.t."
  ]
}